    <statement><p>Find the <m>y</m>-intercept and any <m>x</m>-intercept(s) of the quadratic curve.</p>
<p><m>{y}={16x^{2}-9}</m></p>
<p><m>y</m>-intercept: <fillin characters="16" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p><m>x</m>-intercept(s): <fillin characters="17" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0,-9\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0.75,0\right), \left(-0.75,0\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into <m>{y}={16x^{2}-9}</m>, and we have <m>y=-9</m>.</p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,-9)</m>.</p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>y=0</m> into <m>{y}={16x^{2}-9}</m>, and then solve for <m>x</m>.</p>
<p>For this problem, the polynomial can be factored:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = {16x^{2}-9} \\
   0 \amp = {16x^{2}-9} \\
   0 \amp = (4x - 3)(4x + 3) \\
   4x - 3 = 0     \quad \amp \text{or} \quad 4x + 3 = 0 \\
   4x      = 3 \quad \amp \text{or} \quad 4x = -3 \\
   x          = 0.75 \quad \amp \text{or} \quad x = -0.75
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercepts are <m>(0.75,0)</m> and <m>(-0.75,0)</m>.</p>
</solution>
